<HEADLINE>
<P>
CARTER GIVES LIFT TO VIKINGS; 
</P>
<P>
INTERCONFERENCE: FLEA-FLICKER HELPS VIKINGS DEFEAT DENVER, 27-22. BRONCOS BLOW 
16-0 FIRST-HALF LEAD AFTER ELWAY LEAVES WITH FOOT INJURY. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MINNEAPOLIS 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Minnesota Vikings spent the last month and a half waiting for a big play. 
Sunday night, Anthony Carter and Rich Gannon made one happen. 
</P>
<P>
Carter jumped over Alton Montgomery to catch a long touchdown pass from Gannon 
with 14:04 left as Vikings halted a five-game losing streak with a 27-22 
victory over the Denver Broncos. 
</P>
<P>
The Vikings had the ball on their own 44-yard line when Gannon handed the ball 
off to Herschel Walker, who took a step toward the line and pitched it back to 
Gannon. Gannon threw the ball high and deep even though Montgomery had tight 
coverage on Carter. 
</P>
<P>
"I just thought, 'What the heck?' and threw it up for A.C. to make the play," 
Gannon said. "I knew Anthony could go up and get it." 
</P>
<P>
Carter leaped to take the ball away from Montgomery at the 10, avoided Dennis 
Smith to stay in bounds, and trotted in for the score to complete the 56-yard 
play. 
</P>
<P>
Carter was one of many big-name players to be criticized as Minnesota (2-6), 
the defending NFC Central champion, got off to its worst start since 1961. A 
dropped pass by Carter led directly to a loss to Tampa Bay, and he also dropped 
two passes in last week's loss to Green Bay. 
</P>
<P>
But Sunday he caught five passes for 146 yards, and came up with the biggest 
play of the game. 
</P>
<P>
Just the fact that the Vikings won was amazing. The fact that the Broncos blew 
another big lead wasn't. Denver has led at halftime in all eight games but is 
3-5. The Broncos have been outscored, 135-59, after halftime this season. 
</P>
<P>
The AFC's Super Bowl representative last season, Denver lost for the fourth 
time in five games and is off to its worst start in a non-strike season since 
1975. John Elway hurt his toe and arch after leading the Broncos to a 16-0 
first-half lead and backup quarterback Gary Kubiak was intercepted three times, 
once for a touchdown by Joey Browner. 
</P>
<P>
Did Elway's absence change the complexion of the game? 
</P>
<P>
"That's a crazy question," receiver Mark Jackson said. "Of course it did." 
</P>
<P>
"If you're a backup quarterback in this league, it's your job," Kubiak said. 
"You have to handle it." 
</P>
<P>
He didn't. Gannon, meanwhile, won for the first time in five starts in relief 
of Wade Wilson, who is out with a thumb injury. 
</P>
</TEXT>
