<HEADLINE>
<P>
1,000 TAKE A WALK TO RAISE MONEY FOR AIDS SERVICES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
More than 1,000 people raised $205,000 for AIDS service providers by walking 
downtown Los Angeles streets Sunday in the new "Eastside AIDS-Thon," designed 
to highlight the rising incidence of the deadly disease among blacks, Latinos, 
Asians and other minorities. 
</P>
<P>
The turnout did not meet the expectations of organizers, whose goal was 5,000 
participants bringing in $350,000. 
</P>
<P>
But "it's the first year. We're very pleased," said Keith Malone of the AIDS 
Healthcare Foundation, which financed the event. "There will be a second one." 
</P>
<P>
More than 20 agencies involved with acquired immune deficiency syndrome worked 
together on the walk-a-thon, conceived in part to break what they consider a 
monopoly on fund raising by the more famous AIDS Project Los Angeles "AIDS 
Walk." Proceeds in this year's AIDS Walk were $2.3 million. 
</P>
